Introduction

(1) One of the most burning questions that everyone has certainly thought about at least once is: is it possible to live forever? Most likely not… But Preston Joregeson is definitely intrigued by this possibility and so are we. We wonder: what factors are there that we can learn from animals and their anatomy to elongate a human’s lifespan as long as we can? Perhaps we need to specificially consider metabolic rates, as suggested by some research. Thus, this report will thoroughly look into these claims and will use models and analyses to answer the following questions:

Research Questions:

  1. Is there evidence that supports the claim: Slowing the metabolic rate (eg. by intermittent fasting) may increase lifespan?

  2. Is there a relationship between metablic rate and lifespan and is it nonlinear? Even after transformations?

  3. If we reduce a crab-eating racoon’s (Procyon cancirvorus, HAGRID = 1898) metabolic rate by 50%, what is its estimated mean life span?

The objective of this report is to review the AnAge data to answer these questions to ultimately uncover which factors are related to lifespan to attain the dream of immortality. (2) The AnAge Database of Animal Ageing and Longevity is a “curated database of ageing and lifehistory in animals” that was “primarily developed for comparative biology studies”. This report will analyze 347 observations of 14 variables from an AnAge data file called the ‘anage-chordata-data.csv’. It contains information of animals in the Chordata phylum (animals with spinal cords). Entries with missing variables were removed. The variables are:

Variables

HAGRID: Human Ageing Genomic Resources ID (A unique ID for each entry).

Kingdom: the taxonomic classication of the species (also for variables: phylum, class, order, family genus, and species).

Common.name: common name for the animal (the name used by ordinary people, not scientists).

Maximum.longevity.yrs: maximum longevity (lifespan), in years.

Body.mass.g: typical adult body mass, in grams.

Metabolic.rate: typical resting metabolic rate (rate of energy use) in Watts.

Temperature: typical body temperature in Kelvin.

(3) Overall, the final findings of this report will include the discussion of the distribution of a specie’s maximum longevity lifespan and their metabolic rate. We will also look into the relationship (before and after transformation) between metabolism rates and maximum lifespans, and how it’s non linear but negatively correlated. In addition, this report will uncover how a crab-eating raccoon’s lifespan is affected if its metabolic rate reduces by 50% and how it is actually expected to live about 1 year more from this change.

Exploratory Data Analysis

(1) We first create a new variable called ‘Metabolic.by.mass’. This variable divides variable ‘Metabolic.rate’ by ‘Body.mass.g’, which is the amount of energy used per unit of body mass. This would allow us to compar animals of different sizes. We will use ‘Metabolic.by.mass’ instead of ‘Metabolic.rate’ for the rest of the report.

(2) The key variables that we explore for the research questions are: ‘Metabolic.by.mass’ and ‘Max.longevity.yrs’. ‘Max.longevity.yrs’ is the observation’s maximum lonevity of lifespan measured in years. To execute univariate EDA on these variables, (5) we’ll use the summary of their data points and histograms to display these variables for it is necessary to understand their distribution and their characteristics within the AnAge data.

The summary statistics of ‘Maximum.longevity.yrs’ is: the minimum lifespan is 2.5 years, the maximum is 122.5 years, the median is 12.9 years, and the mean is 16.01 years.

The summary statistics of ‘Metabolic Rate by Mass’ is: the minimum metabolic rate is 4.543e-05 watts/g, the maximum is 4.143e-02 watts/g, the median is 3.023e-03 watts/g, and the mean is 4.143e-02 watts/g.

Histograms of key variables

Notice how the histogram of metabolic by mass exponentailly decreases in frequency when metabolic by mass increases by 0.005, whereas (3) the histogram of maximum longevity years start to exponentially decrease when it passes 30 years. To answer our research questions, our response variable will be the maximum longevity years, and our main explanatory variable is metabolic by mass. Scatter plot of key variables & Correlation

The scatter plot from Figure 2 shows that there doesn’t exist a linear relationship between ‘Metabolic.by.mass’ and ‘Maximum.longevity.yrs’ with its low correlation of -0.385. There is, however, an attempt of a negative correlated association and there are many outliers from the clump formed in the bottom left corner of the plot. Our key observations so far: there are many signs of outliers from both scatter plots and box plots we made for multivariate EDA, and there are heavily skewed distribution with a long tail from our histograms we made for univariate EDA. Thus, both multivariate and univariate EDAs strongly imply to transform both ‘Metabolic.by.mass’ and ‘Maximum.longevity.yrs’ using log. Log will allow the data to be normalized and more linear. In that case, new variables will be created and added to our AnAge data: ‘log_max.long.yrs’ and ‘log_metabolic.by.mass’. Modeling & Diagnostics

Let’s now make a linear model to predict ‘Maximum.longevity.yrs’ using ‘Metabolic.by.mass’ with their transformed versions. First we will make a linear model with these transformed variables and make a scatter plot again like we did for Figure 3.

(1) Let \(M = log(Maximum.longevity.yrs)\) and \(R = log(metabolic.by.mass)\). Thus our linear model is: \[M \sim \beta_0 + \beta_1 * R\]

Then we’ll add a red fitted line that can be created from the linear model we just made. This new plot is shown on Figure 5.

Scatter Plot of Log Metabolic by Mass and Log Maximum Longevity Years with Fitted Line

The scatter plot with the red fitted line (Figure 5) shows that it does an only decent job of showing its relationship. However, the data points are not strongly correlated enough to make accurate predictions using the red fitted line. There is still much more room for improvement to make better predictions. (2) Thus, we will use smoothing spline to make improvement on the fitting of the plot of log Maximum Longevity of Years and log of Metabolic by Mass. Smoothing spline will create more flexible fitted lines so that it is much more effective to understand the variable’s relationship. We’ll do this by first fitting five models with different effective degrees of freedom (df): 3, 4, 5, 6, 7. Then we’ll create smoothing splines based on the degrees of freedom and see how all the different lines fit the data. This is shown on Figure 6.

Scatter Plot with Smoothing Splines

Figure 6 shows a scatter plot of all color-coded fitted lines based on their effective degrees of freedom. Notice how as the degrees of freedom increase, the fitted line becomes less linear and more sensitive to the data points as it runs through the data. In other words, as the degrees of freedom increases, the line becomes more fitted and more accurate to the data distribution, leading to better predictions of Maximum Longevity years from Metatbolic by Mass.

Let’s further analyze the models to determine which model is the best fit for the data. (3) We can do this by observing their prediction error by using cross-validation with five-folds and by comparing the linear models with the spline models. This method will allow us to compare average prediction errors and standard errors between the models. We will indicate the best model by finding the model with the lowest average prediction error. First, let’s see how the models’ prediction error and standard error compare through graphs:

Data Frame of All Average MSE and SSD

Data Frame of All Average MSE and SSD

Both graphs above show each model’s errors based on their degrees of freedom from our selected range: 3 to 7. As both plots have stated, the linear model is represented when df = 2 (though it does not have the degrees of freedom of 2) for graph visual purposes. Easily, we can notice that the model with the degrees of freedom of 5 has the lowest average MSE. To confirm this, we can look at all the recorded average MSE and standard errors:

Thus, our results show that the model with the smoothing spline with the df of 5 is the best predictor log maximum longevity years with the MSE of about 0.358 and the standard error of about 0.00858.

Let’s move onto the next step to dive deeper into our best predicted model based on its errors. (4) We’ll first look at its residual plots and qq plots, which is shown on Figure 7.

Residual vs Fitted Plot & Q-Q Plot of Model of df = 5

Based on our best model and its diagnostic plots shown on Figure 7, we could say that the model actually fits our data pretty well. Residual vs Fitted plot shows that all of the errors show evidence of constant variance around 0. In addition., our Q-Q plot shows that the error is mainly normally distributed.

(5) A nonformal analysis on our best model with other model further validates its best fit for the data. Looking at the standard errors, our model has one of the most relatively low SSD, which implies that our best model is one of the most consistent.

(6) Now we want to make official analyses claims by boostrapping on our model. Since our Q-Q plot shows a sufficient normally distribution and our residual plot shows signs of constant variance around 0, we will do a non-parametric bootstrap.

Results

(1) Let’s now officially determine whether animals with lower metabolic rates have longer lifespans. Our first key observation was that the relationship between the transformed Metabolic by Mass and Maximum Longevity Years have a negative correlation. However, due to our cross-validation we calculated in ‘Modelling and Diagnostics’, we see that the best model has 5 degrees of freedom. This implies that association is not linear. In addition, the negative correlation means that as the metabolic rate increases, the maximum longevity years decreases. This implies that the lower the animal’s metabolic rate, it is safe to predict that the lifespan would be higher.

(2) Now, per Preson Jorgenson’s request, let’s look into the crab-eating racoon and its features:

Its metabolic rate by mass is about 0.00223 and its maximum longevity lifespan in years is 19. Now let’s calculate its metabolic rate if it would have its rate were 50% smaller. We’ll do this by first dividing its metabolic rate by mass by half and then log it: \(log(0.002231034/2) = -6.798437\). Now let’s estimate its mean lifespan of an animal with those characters based on our best model that has 5 degrees of freedom. We can use non-parametric bootstrapping to do so by using the pivotal confidence interval and 1000 bootstrap iterations.

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  predictions
## t = 636.17, df = 999, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  20.15376 20.27848
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  20.21612

The one sample t-test shows that the mean estimate lifespan of an animal with those characteristics is 20.11135.

(3) It is also important to understand the 95% confidence interval for our point estimate. This is because we want to understand what range our point estimate will be and be 95% confident that it is. We can see that from the t-test that our 95% confidence interval of the maximum longevity years of a racooon with 50% reduced metabolic rate by mass is [20.04628, 20.17641] with the mean of 20.11135. Again, the crab-eating raccoon’s maximum longevity lifespan is 19 years, which is not included in the confidence interval. This implies that there is sufficient evidence to claim that reducing a raccoon’s metabolic rate by 50% will ensure an increase in their maximum longevity lifespan.

Conclusions

(1) In conclusion, we see that there is definitely a negative correlated relationship between an animal’s maximum lifespan and their metabolic rate by mass. This means that as an animal’s metabolic rate by mass decrease, the animal’s maximum lifespan increases. All of our scatter plots and analyses showed, however, that this relationship is not exactly linear, even after transforming the variables by log. We also conducted cross-validation with 5 folds to understand the models based on transformed variables. From these multiple analyses, we can conclude that a nonlinear spline model of 5 effective degrees of freedom was the best predicting model.

(2) In addition, Preston Jorgenson can conclude that reducing the crab-eating raccoon’s metabolic rate by 50% would cause its lifespan to increase. We discovered this by finding its confidence interval by doing non-parametric bootstrapping for 1000 iterations, and the crab-eating raccoon’s maximum longevity lifespan was not within the confidence interval, proving to be significant. This implies that the difference between the crab-eating raccon’s lifespan and the mean of the confidence interval is the difference in how much the lifespan would change. This has calculated to be about an increase of 1 year (\(20.111 - 19 = 1.111\)).

(3) Based on the given data from AnAge Dataset, we created ‘Metabolic.by.mass’ by using ‘Metabolic.rate’ and ‘Body.mass.g’ and used it as our main explanatory variable. To claim that this one variable is the sole factor of affecting an animal’s maximum lifespan is limited. There are definitely many more factors that we could’ve explored from the AnAge Dataset and even beyond this dataset. However, it was appropriate to mainly examine an animal’s metabolic rate in order to answer our research questions. In addition, to have a clear understanding of what the research questions wanted to examine, it is also important to maintain simplicity and focusing on key variables such as ‘Metabolic.by.mass’. Overall, it would have been more interesting to observe other factors to see their interactions with maximum lifespan as well to make further discussions about the possibility of immortality.
